Lets choose , flights in August and drop out some columns.

library(dplyr)

flight2019_raw<- flight2019_raw %>% 
  filter(_=="", _=="", =="2019-08") %>% 
  select(!c(..,..,.kg.,.kg.,.kg.))

To mark the location of airports, we need coordinates in airport data.

xxx_join(x, y, by=join_by(key)) : Add columns from y to x, matching observations based on the keys

https://rpubs.com/williamsurles/293454
flight2019_code<- flight2019_raw %>% left_join(select(airport,IATA, longitude, latitude), by = join_by(== IATA))
is.na(flight2019_code)%>%table()
## .
## FALSE  TRUE 
## 11760    18
flight2019_code%>%filter(!complete.cases(flight2019_code))

Missing values are in coordinates columns only. Should we remove them?

/

We can fill the blanks!

List up the airports without coordinates and lets google them.

missingIATAlist<-flight2019_code%>%filter(!complete.cases(flight2019_code))%>%select()%>%unique

How do we put the coordinates?

missingIATA_latlon 
##          [,1]     [,2]
## [1,] 34.79527 138.1796
## [2,] 21.12031 107.4161
## [3,] 32.07083 120.9756
missingIATA<- cbind(missingIATAlist, missingIATA_latlon) 
colnames(missingIATA)<- c("code", "lat", "lon")


for (i in 1:nrow(missingIATA)) {
  code <- missingIATA$code[i]
  lat <- missingIATA$lat[i]
  lon <- missingIATA$lon[i]
  flight2019_code$latitude[flight2019_code$==code]<- lat
  flight2019_code$longitude[flight2019_code$==code]<- lon
}

is.na(flight2019_code)%>%table
## .
## FALSE 
## 11778

Mark on a map

Lets split the data into arrivals and departures for comparison.

library(ggplot2)

flight2019arr<- flight2019_code%>%filter(_=="")
flight2019dep<- flight2019_code%>%filter(_=="")

Again, when making a chart using ggplot, we stack layers.

As a canvas, we create a empty world map and declare as p.

mymap <- map_data("world")
p<- ggplot(mymap, aes(x=long, y=lat)) + 
  geom_map(data = mymap, map = mymap, aes(map_id=region), col = "gray", fill = "white")

Marker size based on the number of passengers.

p_point <- p + 
  flight2019arr%>% geom_point(mapping=aes(x=longitude, y=latitude, size=..),
                              colour = 'blue',alpha=0.1) +
  labs(title="2019 8       ", size=" ()")

p_point

p_line <- p +

                              colour = 'blue',alpha=0.1) +
  flight2019arr%>% geom_segment(mapping=aes(y=37.449419, x=126.451328, xend=longitude, yend = latitude), linewidth=0.1 )

And then repeat the same process twice? Well.?

facet_wrap(vars(grouping variables), nrow= ) : creates graphs for each groups in the grid set by ncol or nrow

p + flight2019arr%>%filter(==""|=="") %>%
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=longitude, y=latitude, size=..),
                                  colour = 'blue',alpha=0.2)+
  facet_wrap(vars(), nrow=2)+
  labs(title="2019 8       ", size=" ()")

Lets compare from different point. Read the data of year 2020 and cleanse it through the same process.

When you repeat the same process for different data, be aware of what point you need to make a change in accordance with the new data.

flight2020_raw<- read.csv(path2, fileEncoding = "cp949")
flight2020_raw<- flight2020_raw%>%
  filter(_=="", _=="", =="2020-08") %>%
  select(!c(..,..,.kg.,.kg.,.kg.))

flight2020_code<- flight2020_raw %>% left_join(select(airport,IATA, longitude, latitude), by = c(""= "IATA"))
missingIATAlist<-flight2020_code%>%filter(!complete.cases(flight2020_code))%>%select()%>%unique

For 2020, theres only one airport missing the coordinates. And fortunately, it was already included in 2019 also. We are reuse the data then.

flight2020_code$longitude[flight2020_code$=="VDO"]<- missingIATA$lon[missingIATA$code=="VDO"]
flight2020_code$latitude[flight2020_code$=="VDO"]<- missingIATA$lat[missingIATA$code=="VDO"]

is.na(flight2020_code)%>%table
## .
## FALSE 
##  4472
flight2020arr<- flight2020_code%>%filter(_=="")
flight2020dep<- flight2020_code%>%filter(_=="")

Marker size based on the number of passengers in 2020.

p_point2020<- p+ flight2020arr%>% geom_point(mapping=aes(x=longitude, y=latitude, size=..),
                                          colour = 'blue',alpha=0.1)+
  labs(title="2020 8       ", size=" ()")

Lets put two graphs from different dataframe side by side using grid.arrange

library(gridExtra)

## 
##     combine
grid.arrange(p_point, p_point2020, nrow=2)

What can you tell? Any sggestion for improvement?

To apply the same visualization criteria, lets combine two separate dateframes using rbind()

flight2yrs<- rbind(flight2019_code, flight2020_code)

In one dataframe? facet_wrap()

Another way to set facet variables : .~var name

p + flight2yrs%>%filter(_=="")%>% geom_point(mapping=aes(x=longitude, y=latitude, size=..),
                                colour = 'blue',alpha=0.1) +
  facet_wrap(.~ , nrow=2) +
  labs(title="2019 8, 2020 8       ", size=" ()")

we can even apply two variables for facet.

p_point_1920<- p + flight2yrs%>% geom_point(mapping=aes(x=longitude, y=latitude, size=..),
                                            colour = 'blue',alpha=0.1) +
  facet_wrap(.~  +_ , nrow=2) +
  labs(title="2020 8       ", size=" ()")

p_point_1920

Lastly, lets save the chart using ggsave().

It saves the last plot you displayed.

ggsave("ArrICN_19n20Aug.png", width = 11, height = 8, units = "in")
